    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1937-12-26T23:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1937-12-26T23:00:00-05:00" n="936"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d936">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.00/14194: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Hankow</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-12-27T12:00:00+08:00"
                            >December 27, 1937—noon</date>.<lb/>[Received 1:05 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>109. Following from Colonel Stilwell for War Department.</p>
                <quote rend="blockquote">
                    <p>Red proposals in conference here still vague. Essence of demands is to
                        mobilize the masses, unify the command, standardize equipment. <pb
                            facs="0845" n="838" xml:id="pg_838"/> Concrete methods of accomplishment
                        not stated. Reds claim they will support Chiang Kai Shek and will take part
                        in Government if the Kuomintang so requests. They claim their idea is not to
                        reorganize the Government but simply to strengthen it by mutual assistance
                        development of the Kuomintang and the Communists. They do not want the help
                        of armed forces of foreign powers, but want foreign experts as technical
                        advisers. Nationality not specified. They are suspicious of the present
                        German advisers.</p>
                    <p>Military situation in Yangtze Valley unchanged.</p>
                </quote>
                <p>Repeated to Peiping.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Johnson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
